author: DANIEL McKILLOP The Daily News
title: Thunderbirds cruise
text:
DANIEL McKILLOP/The Daily News TOP NOTCH SWIMMER 
Lady T-birds senior Maddie Houltram glides through the Bullhead City Municipal Swimming Pool during Mohave High School’s home meet on Thursday. Thunderbirds cruise By DANIEL McKILLOP The Daily News MohaveDailyNews.com | 0 comments 
BULLHEAD CITY — The T-birds and the Lady T-birds outnumbered their counterparts and the results did not lie during the Mohave High School’s dual meet at the Bullhead City Municipal Swimming Pool on Thursday. 
Mohave beat Kingman High School Bulldogs 163.0-10.0, Kingman Academy Tigers 157.0-20.0, and the Mohave Accelerated Learning Center Patriots 166-5.0 in combined scores. 
The Mohave boys shut out Kingman Academy 83.0-0, defeated Kingman 80.0-8.0 and MALC 83.0-3.0. 
The Mohave girls knocked off MALC 83.0-2.0, Kingman 83.0-2.0 and Kingman Academy 74.0-20.0. 
“It was a great tuneup race, practice for our next qualifying meet,” T-birds head coach Ed Catalfamo said. “We did a little adjustments with some of our relay teams to try to get state-qualifying times in the 400-meter relay.” 
The T-birds will travel to Yuma to compete in Yuma High School’s Crim Swim state-qualifying meet on Oct. 12, said the five-year Mohave head swimming coach. 
The Lady T-birds are sporting a quartet that is ranked 10th in the Arizona Interscholastic Association Division II rankings. 
The top 24 times earn a spot at the state meet. 
Sophomores Bridget MacDonald, Erin Johnson, Jaylene Seaman and senior Maddie Houltram are ranked 10th after swimming the 200 freestyle relay in 1 minute, 50.92 seconds at the Northwest Arizona Invitational, which was hosted by Flagstaff High School on Sept. 19. 
MacDonald, Houltram, Seaman and Christina Barton are ranked 13th after swimming the 200 medley relay at 2:04.57 in Flagstaff on Sept. 19. 
Four boys made Mohave swimming history by qualifying — up until now — in the 200 freestyle. 
Sophomores Jacob Catalfamo and Dylan Boyd, along with seniors Kyle Morse and Max Rose are ranked 24th after swimming the 200 freestyle relay at 1:42.65 in Flagstaff. 
“My goal for the next invite,” said Catalfamo in reference to the Swim Crim, “is to pull the kids off the 200 and put them in the 400 to try to qualify (more swimmers) for state.”
